Balder</i>, appearances to the contrary notwithstanding."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William De Balderston was born about 1243, in Osbaldeston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married William de Balderston about 1269, in Blackburn, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1243–":"umbes 1243–Surnud","1239–1292":"1239–1292","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1294–Female":"1294–Surnud","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1239":"1239","1332":"1332","1243":"1243","ABT 1269":"umbes 1269","1294":"1294","about 1243":"umbes 1243","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","West Riding, Yorkshire,, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of,Osbaldeston,Lancashire,England":"Osbaldeston, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<Osbaldeston, Blackburn, Lancashire, England>":"Blackburn, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Blackburn, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1243–":"noin 1243–Kuollut","1239–1292":"1239–1292","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1294–Female":"1294–Kuollut","1243–Female":"1243–Kuollut","1239":"1239","1332":"1332","1243":"1243","ABT 1269":"noin 1269","1294":"1294","about 1243":"n